  <tr>
    <td>
      <table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="center">
        <tr>
          <td bgcolor="black">
            <table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="4">
              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="" colspan="2" align="center"><b><font face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" size="1" color="mintcream">T O P I C&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;R E V I E W</font></b></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#37437B" valign="top" width="100" nowrap><font color="white" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" size="2"><b>Nummularia</b></font></td>
                <td bgcolor="#37437B" valign="top" width="100%"><font color="white" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;01/06/2004&nbsp;: 2:56:21 PM</small><hr size="1"><span class="spnMessageText"> This is a lecture from my mother, who got it from her friend who was at the lecture in Rome.  Yes, it was a long time ago, during the Vietnam war and all that, but even these words have impact upon today's world.<br /><br />Yes, it's long, but it's worth the read.  And yes, this priest does manage to insult everyone under the sun... except the Irish!<br /><br /><b><u><center>Portions of a lecture by: Fr. Martin given to Loyola University students Sept. 26, 1963, Rome.</b></u></center><br /><br />…For, the phenomenon that is modern America is a fascinating one.  Never in the history of man has there been anything quite like it.  A glance over the entire panorama of human history reveals that no power resembling America has ever emerged on the human scene.<br />The long, winding road over which the cavalcade of human development has wound and twisted and turned and stumbled throughout the centuries, is strewn on wither side with the bleaching bones of great men, the shattered structures of mighty empires, the crushed columns of colonial powers, the charnel-heaps of once dominant nations.  Military empires like the Assyrian, Babylonian, the Persian, the Russian (of Peter the Great), the Sumerian.  Dynastic empires like the Egyptian, the Burbon, the Hapsburg, the Inca, the Ming, the Mongol, the Romanoff.  Colonial empires like the British, French, German, Portuguese, the Spanish.  Economic-military empires like the Austro-Hungarian, the Byzantine, the Carthaginian.  Religious empires like that Islam, like the Ottoman Turk, like the Holy Roman Empire (which its enemies said was neither Holy nor Roman nor an empire).<br /><br />Each one had its day, glistened and gleamed under the sun on the human horizon, shone with special brilliance all its own at its apogee, and finally sunk beneath the rim of human endurance and disappeared forever.  Some like Byzance, like Carthage, like the Inca, perished overnight, as it were, came crashing down at one fell blow dragging with them the lives and fortunes of millions.  Others, like Rome, like Britain, slipped into and fortunes of millions.  Others, like Rome, like Britain, slipped into decay slowly, imperceptibly, dissolved steadily under the hammer-blows of fierce, primitive forces ranging around its encrusted imperial walls and beating at its ageing limbs.<br /><br />Others still were created by the genius of one man, an Alexander of Macedonia, a Genghis Khan, a Hitler, a Napoleon, a Tamerlane.  Each one of these was the child of a storm, born from some diseased matrix, springing from the some ruins, economic, social, religious, political.  Each one grasped at greatness greedily, and each one was bewitched by the long dreaming harmonies of his imperial resolution, his power ambition.  Each one rode for a time, securely, heroically, generously, triumphantly, in the eye of the hurricane they evoked, immune from the destruction, the chains, the misery they forced on others.  And each one was finally snatched up and whirled away to perdition, helpless as a straw in the cyclone he had engendered, battered to bits by the contrapuntal furies he had let loose as his slaves.<br /><br />Yet, no matter, no matter how high they spiraled, individuals or empires, no matter how their supremacy scintillated, no matter how their dominance dashed all opposition to defeat, no matter how brilliant their battle-strategy, no matter how cunning their characters, or how cohesive their coagulation of captive countries, peoples and nations, or how effective and extensive the elongated, stick well of their trading, their exporting, their economic feats, no matter how glorious their final resistance, how dignified their last tottering steps, no matter!  They went down to the dust as hated things, and the ruins of Byzance, of Berlin, of Babylon, of Memphis, of Thebes, the dismembered structures of Britain, France, there are mere maudlin memorials to their excesses and reminders of their profound mistakes, their ultimate inhumanity to man.<br /><br />None of them, no, not one of them, ever resembled the United States of America as a world power.  But don’t get me wrong, or rather; don’t get a wrong idea of the greatness of that phenomenon, the United States.  It is not that you are the greatest military power now or ever, (you actually are that).  It is not so much that you came to the aid of Europe twice in the same half-century and snatched this assembly of free but impotent nations from the overwhelming, grasping fist of the Teutonic dictatorship and imperialism, (this you did).  It is not so much that you fed us all gratuitously when we were starving, (you did).  It is not that you put us all back on our feet financially and economically when we had not a red cent to rattle on a tombstone, (you did).  It is not so much that you have been, that you still are, and you will be for a long time to come, our sole bulwark against militant communism, in South American, in Southeast Asia, in Europe.  It is not so much that you manufactured the shield behind which Europe shelters and that you only have the strength to hold that shield, to wield it, and the guarantee that its impregnability. All this is true.<br /><br />You have to patrol the seven seas with fleets.  You have to man the air lanes of the heavens.  You have to a 24 hours watch on the intercontinental missile paths.  You have had to set up and maintain a global intelligence system.  You have to spearhead the long leaping bounds of free man into outer space.  You have to contribute billions each year so that emergent nations will not fall into the communist orbit.  You have to finance the United Nations operations in the Congo, along the Gaza strip, throughout Yemen, on the Syrian-Israel border.  You cleared the Suez Canal for the Egyptians.  You pick up the lion’s share of the yearly tap for the United Nations.  When disaster hits Holland and its dykes burst, you rush to help.  When Skopje in Yugoslavia shivers and falls on its inhabitants, you fly immediately.  When Agadir in Africa shakes and chatters, you are there.  Your academic foundations finance the rest of the world.  Your charitable contributions keep institutions going all over the glove.  You make the single largest contribution to the upkeep of the Vatican.  You maintain, all this time, the highest standard of living at home within the States.  In short, you must carry the free world and a good deal of the non-free world on your back, as a colossus, easily, gently, generously, firmly, resolutely.  You are the foundations of its hope, the source of its strength, its final refuge and bastion, its ultimate guarantee that the world will not perish from badness, on the natural plane.<br /><br />Yet, none of all this is the foundation of your greatness, nor are these. Singly or collectively your undoubted title to being and incomparable phenomenon, a thing unknown before this, a people, a nation, a polity, such as this glove has never seen before, such as men dreamt of in philosophical reverie.<br /><br />Your title, your description, the nobility that sets you apart is something to which you yourselves don’t seem to advert.  It is the behavior of a gentle, Herculean-muscled, humanistic, giant, bearing unbearable burdens with facility, refusing to be goaded into anger, willingly assuming the protection of what is good, noble, is human in this world.  Patiently submitting to the foolishnesses of those who depend on you, continually avoid petty reactions to the pettiness of the people you love, matching the small-minded, the cribbed, the cabined, the confined mentality with the comprehensive outlook, the confident restraint of a huge person who knows that at a pinch he can crush anything or anybody in living radius.<br /><br />The very people you saved, then you nourished, then you armed, and now you finance, these same have called you all the names under the sun, have bid you to go home.  “Yankee, go home!” Scribbled on the walls of Mayfair, London.  “Ami americain va-t-en chez toi et fiche-mous la paix”, shouted in Paris at Gruenther, at Ridgeway, at Eisenhower, at Rusk.  Diese Amerikaner sind immer die selben grossen Buben, sneered at you in the Bonn and Dusseldorf and Hamburg.  “Stinking American devil”, scrawled in human excrement on embassy cars in Tokyo.<br /><br />Your embassies in Beirut, Cairo, Copenhagen, in Paris and Rome have been besieged by people wearing clothes you supplied them.  Your consulates and legations in Damascus, Bjakarta, in Caracas, in Helsinki and in Milan have been sacked and pillaged.  USIS offices throughout the world have been burnt and razed to the ground.  Americans are continually being over-charged in hotels, gypped in shops, cheated by bootblacks in Athens, in Istanbul, in Karachi.  You have been continually blamed by that lord of gobbledygook and the permanent inhabitant of cloud nine, Nehru.  Yet you never have deserted helping him.  Your soldiers have been killed with the weapons you supplied to the new states, yet you did not send a gunboat or a bomber to blast them to kingdom come.  You have been attacked, pilloried, blamed, excoriated, condemned, spat upon.  Yet, you have not allowed this to affect your steady march.  Nor have you allowed imperialist dreams to grip you imagination.  You are, in brief, almost the incarnation of the person immortalized by Kipling in his poem IF:<br /><br /><center><i>“If you can keep your head when all about you<br />are losing theirs and blaming it on you.<br />If you can trust yourself, when all men doubt you,<br />But make allowance for their doubting too.<br />If you can wait, but not be tired by waiting;<br />Or being lied about, don’t deal in lies;<br />Or being hated, don’t give way to hating;<br />And yet don’t look too good, nor talk too wise.<br /><br />If you can dream, but not make dreams your master.<br />If you can think, but not make thought your aim.<br />If you can meet with Triumph and Disaster,<br />And treat those two impostors just the same.<br /><br />If you can bear to hear the truth you’ve spoken,<br />Twisted by knaves to make a trap for fools,<br />Or watch the things you gave your life to,<br />Broken, and stoop and build them up<br />With outworn tools…”</i></center><br /><br />And after two or three more verses he ends up, “then you’ll be a man”.  Therein lies your true greatness, because this is what distinguishes you from everyone else, from all other world powers up to this.<br /><br />So, take heart, Americans!  Take Heart!  And, for the love of God and the love of man, don’t lose heart!  Be brave, but don’t be rash.  Be courageous, but don’t be headstrong.  Be proud, but don’t be arrogant.  Be strong, but don’t be cruel.  Be dominant, but don’t be domineering.  Be patient, but don’t lose interest.  Be our patrons, but don’t be patronizing.  Be big, but don’t be too big for your pants.  Be modest, but don’t be ashamed.  Above all, don’t be ashamed!  Don’t be ashamed of what you are.  Let none of these European pipsqueaks makes you feel that you are inferior in anything.  Neither British upper-class with their dreadful, penniless, decadent snobbery, nor gesticulating French thinker or politician with his mental diarrhea, his congenital volatility, his profound stupidity, his complete lack of humanity, nor any German nouveau riche with his fearful fascination for machines, his satanic lust for power, his fatal contempt for the weak, his periodic brain-storms, his crass sybaritic pig like dependence on food, nor any dancing false-tongued Italian with his fakery, his earthiness, his total incapability to tell the naked truth (the only naked thing he can face is a woman’s body), his innate lack of dignity and self-respect, his utter independability.  Nor Spaniards with their forthright bluntness, nor Greeks with half-Semitic vagueness, nor Swiss with their hard, glossy, metallic materialism, nor Scandinavians with their smelly morality or the lack of it, nor even the Irish with their poetry, their wit, their nomadic instincts, their faith, nor Turks with their age-old, myopic, primitive, dull, inhuman, materialistic behaviorism, none of them, not one of them, can match you in the total sum of virtues, social and personal and national, which you have accumulated in that most peculiar of all polities, that most unique of all national groupings, that new thing, that rare thing, called the United States of America.<br /><br />Sure, if I am jealous of your material welfare because I am a poor penny scraping French government employee, If I am jealous because I am a British imperialist without an empire, if I am jealous because I am a German out of whom you beat the living guts, of course, I am going to see the bad things.  Like a beetle, I shall flit and fly over the bed of roses in your American garden, over the ranges of tulips, over the beautiful passion flowers, out over the heavy, fertile hanging fruit trees, out to the dark corners of your garden and there light upon the few dung-heaps that exist and rollick about and roll on them saying all the while. “What a filthy place this America is, what filthy people these Americans are!”<br /><br />Every American I meet in America or from it will be a cigar-chomping, savage, slave-driving capitalist, harassed by B-girls and Call-girls.  Every woman and girl from America will be either a gold digger from Broadway or the image of the gilded girl from Hollywood.  Every crime in America will be a common, everyday occurrence in every American home.  And Americans will nourish themselves on popcorn, chewing-gum, and t-bone steaks, will live in motels, drive Cadillacs, wear jeans, strain their backs and smash their marriage-life by too much looking at television, and dislocate their sacroiliacs with continual twisting.  No!  This the patent distortion, the product of the small pinched mind, of the men or the nation or people mindful of their past greatness, now with their hands out or their pockets full due to your generosity.<br /><br />There is perhaps only one more thing lacking to America that is reach the uppermost point of national greatness, national greatness such as is reserved for them in history.  They have yet to be driven into the ultimate corner, have yet to fight themselves out of it, have yet to be strained to the gates of death, and return from that shadowy border that separates life from death.  They have never yet been driven, on to one of those crags of history, a lone isolated position from which there is neither retreat nor escape, which promises only extinction or survival.<br /><br /><i><center>“If you can make one lump of all your winnings.<br />And risk it on one turn of pitch-and-toss,<br />And lose and start again at your beginnings,<br />And never breathe a word about your loss.<br /><br />If you can force your heart and nerve and sinew<br />To serve your turn long after they are gone,<br />And so hold on when there is nothing in you<br />Except the will which says to them: hold on!”</center></i><br /><br />That would be the ultimate test, a test I am confident America would and could pass, just as sure as she can the other tests, which Kipling sings of:<br /><br /><i><center>“If you can talk with crowds, nor lose your virtue,<br />and walk with Kings, nor lose the common touch,<br />If neither foes nor loving friends can hurt you,<br />If all men count with you but none too much.<br /><br />If you can fill the unforgiving minute<br />With sixty seconds worth of distance run,<br />Yours is the earth and everything that’s in it,<br />And … what’s more… you’ll be a man my song!”</center></i><br /></span></font></td>
              </tr>
